title: Measurements of nuclear gamma-ray line emission in interactions of protons and alpha particles with N, O, Ne and Si.

x4freetext: Measurements of nuclear gamma-ray line emission in
interactions of protons and alpha particles with N, O,
Ne and Si.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.83, p.024603 (2011)

x4freetext: A gas cell containing the target elements Ne, N and O,
all employed gases were of natural isotopic
composition were used. Three different molecular gases
were used for the irradiation of N and O. A N(2)O gas
target was used for studying lines produced by
reactions of low-energy proton and alpha-particle beams
with N-14 and O-16. At energies where spallation
reactions of O-16 may produce N-14 lines, N(2) and
CO(2) were used separately for measurements on N-14 and
O-16, respectively. For the irradiations of Si with
proton beams of 10, 15 and 20 MeV were used a 21.1-
mg/cm**2-thick foil of Si of natural isotopic
composition placed at the center of the empty gas cell.
The gas cell has been built as a 13-cm-long aluminum
cylinder of 3.8 cm inner diameter. Two narrower
sections were placed at each end of the cylinder, each
of them holding a 6-mum-thick Mylar foil. These
sections had 12 and 20 mm diameter at the beam entrance
and exit, respectively. The total length of the cell
between the two foils was 18.7 cm.
Gamma-rays were detected with four Ge detectors
equipped with Bismuth germanate (BGO) shields for
Compton suppression. Two segmented clover detectors
(VEGA) from the Euroball setup were placed at angles
of 120 and 135 degrees with respect to the beam
direction and at 40 cm from the center of the gas cell.
Another clover detector- a prototype of the Exogam
setup and a single coaxial Ge detector from the Eurogam
phase I were situated at 90 degree and 20 cm and at 30
degree and 17.5 cm from the gas target,respectively.
Data for the 13 individual crystals with standard
Nuclear Instrumentation Module (NIM) electronics and
the data acquisition system NARVAL were used.
.Uncertainties on the differential cross section
data include the statistical uncertainty and
uncertainties due to background subtraction, dead-time
correction and relative detection efficiency.
.The error in the relative efficiencies was 5%
.Uncertainties on acquisition dead times
were estimated in the analyses of isotropic gamma-ray
angular distributions to be less than 3%.
